If you are asking whether there is any special syntax for doing this check: there isn&#39;t.

    var object = {testKey: testKey || null}

is the most concise you can get (ignoring renaming variables).

If you want to avoid repeating the variable name (I can see that there are valid reasons for this, but e.g. strict mode would adequately protect you against typos), then you could update the variable before using it as a property:

    testKey = testKey || null;
    var object = {testKey};

Of course that changes the value of `testKey` so it&#39;s not equivalent to the first code.

