You can use `System.IO.File` to read the file from the path, and then you can parse it and work on it. If you need to make the path more fixable for the application (say you want to change the path), you can just add the path in your web.config, and read that path from inside the code. 

Example: 

web.config 

    &lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot; encoding=&quot;utf-8&quot;?&gt;
    &lt;configuration&gt;
    	&lt;appSettings&gt;
    		&lt;add key=&quot;ConnectionStringsPath&quot; value=&quot;C:\DbConnection.config&quot;/&gt;
    	&lt;/appSettings&gt;
    &lt;/configuration&gt;

Then, I just created a method that returns the `ConnectionString` :

    public static string GetConnectionString(string name)
    {
    	return XDocument.Parse(System.IO.File.ReadAllText(ConfigurationManager.AppSettings[&quot;ConnectionStringsPath&quot;]))
    		.Descendants(&quot;connectionStrings&quot;)
    		.Elements()
    		.Where(x =&gt; x.Attribute(&quot;name&quot;).Value.ToLower().Equals(name.ToLower()))
    		.Select(x =&gt; x.Attribute(&quot;connectionString&quot;).Value)
    		.First();
    }

usage : 

    var connectionString = GetConnectionString(&quot;BarcodeEngineApiContext&quot;);

if you want to go fancy, you can create a simple model to be deserialized. 

example : 

    public class ConnectionString
    {
        public string Provider { get; set; }
    
        public string Name { get; set; }
    
        public string Connection { get; set; }
    }

then adjusting the above method to : 

    public static ConnectionString GetConnectionString(string name)
    {
    	return XDocument.Parse(System.IO.File.ReadAllText(ConfigurationManager.AppSettings[&quot;ConnectionStringsPath&quot;]))
    		.Descendants(&quot;connectionStrings&quot;)
    		.Elements()
    		.Where(x =&gt; x.Attribute(&quot;name&quot;).Value.ToLower().Equals(name.ToLower()))
    		.Select(x =&gt; new ConnectionString()
    		{
    			Name = x.Attribute(&quot;name&quot;).Value,
    			Provider = x.Attribute(&quot;providerName&quot;).Value,
    			Connection = x.Attribute(&quot;connectionString&quot;).Value
    		}
    		).First();
    }

Then you use it like this : 

    var barcode = GetConnectionString(&quot;BarcodeEngineApiContext&quot;);
    var name = barcode.Name;
    var provider = barcode.Provider;
    var connectionString = barcode.Connection;

If you have multiple connectionStrings in the same project, you can create `Enum` with list of connections names, and pass it to the method instead of typing the name manually.

Example : 

     public enum ConnectionStringName
    {
        BarcodeEngineApiContext, 
        SecondConnectionString,
        AnotherConnectionString
    }

and just pass it to the method : 

    var barcode = GetConnectionString(ConnectionStringName.BarcodeEngineApiContext.ToString());

